Furthermore, advanced microscopic techniques and spectroscopic analyses were employed to elucidate the underlying mechanisms linking dynamic imine bond chemistry to the observed emulsion behavior. The morphological changes of CDs-C after the addition of NaOH and HCl were observed using a JEM-2100 high-resolution transmission electron microscope (Fig. 7
                        a, b, c). The TEM images clearly demonstrate the breaking and regeneration of dynamic imine bonds within CDs-C. Upon the introduction of NaOH solution (1 M), the size of CDs-C decreases from 4.4 nm to 2.5 nm (Fig. 7d, e), indicating that the dynamic imine bonds break in an alkaline environment, resulting in the decomposition of CDs-C into CDs-NH2 and cinnamaldehyde. After acid neutralization, the size of CDs-C is essentially restored to its original size (Fig. 7f), indicating the regeneration of CDs-C NPs. Additionally, absorption spectra were used to monitor the structural changes of CDs in alkali solution (Fig. 7g). The results show that at low concentrations of NaOH (1 μM–10 mM), there are no obvious change in the peak position, indicating no effect on the structure of CDs. In contrast, at high concentrations of NaOH (50 mM and 100 mM), the absorption peak at around 266 nm, originated from CDs, completely disappears, and a new peak at 280 nm appears, suggesting the cleavage of imine bond and re-formation of CDs-NH2 and cinnamaldehyde [45]. This result is further confirmed by the FT-IR spectrum. As shown in Fig. 7h, a broad peak centered at ∼1760 cm−1 is attributed to stretching vibration of CO, providing evidence that the imine bond is broken and the aldehyde group is regenerated. These results indicate that, upon increasing the pH to strongly alkaline levels, the dynamic covalent bond dissociates, converting amphiphilic CDs-C NPs into highly hydrophilic CDs-NH2 NPs and surface-inactive cinnamaldehyde. Both substances desorb from the oil–water interface, leading to rapid separation of the oil and water phases in the Pickering emulsions. Moreover, lowering the pH of the aqueous phase allows the cinnamaldehyde in the system to react in situ with hydrophilic CDs-NH2 NPs to re-form amphiphilic CDs-C NPs. Moreover, we have added a comprehensive comparison table (Table S1) that systematically evaluates our carbon dots-based emulsifiers against similar works reported in recent literature. This systematic comparison highlights the significant advancements of our imine-bonded CDs emulsifier over conventional systems across multiple dimensions (see Fig. 8
                        ).
